- Pond Scum

A system of ponds at a casino in Las Vegas is laid out in a checkerboard pattern. At one point, the heights of all the ponds in the system were kept at carefully calibrated heights. They used to be constantly lled or drained as fast as needed to keep them at their constant, pre-set heights. The water owing through the pipes was an amusing spectacle for children to see.

Due to the crumbling economy in Vegas, the pumps in certain of the ponds no longer function correctly, and the heights of these ponds are no longer directly controlled by the computer system.

Pipes connect each pond to its four neighbors (east, west, north, south). If a pond has a broken pump, then water ows through the pipe between two ponds at a rate that is proportional to the di erence in the heights of the water in those ponds. If a pond&#39;s pump is still controlled by the system, then you may assume that it&#39;s height remains constant.

One day, someone lls up the ponds to a certain initial height and then just lets the system take care of itself. Your problem is to compute an estimate of the heights in all variable-height ponds at equilibrium (that is, when the total rate at which water ows into each variable-height, broken-pump ponds from its higher neighbors is equal to the rate owing out to its lower neighbors, so that the pond&#39;s height remains constant). The equilibrium height does not depend on the constant of proportionality that relates di erences in heights to rate of ow.

- Party

Alice wants to throw a party and is deciding whom to call. She has N people to choose from, and she has made up a list of which pairs of these people know each other. She wants to pick as many people as possible, subject to two constraints: at the party, each person should have at least k1 other people whom they know and k2 other people whom they don&#39;t know. (Note that you can&#39;t know or not know yourself. You don&#39;t count in your own computation.)

Input to your program will be a text le called description.txt. The rst line will hold the number k1 and the second line will hold the number k2. The remainder of the le will be a 0-1 adjacency matrix indicating which people know which others. If there is an edge between two people, then they know each other. If not, they don&#39;t. People will be represented numbers from 1 to N. (Part of the problem will be to determine the number N from the adjacency matrix itself.)

Output should consist of a list of integers, one per line, in the le party.txt of the people who should be invited to the party.

For example, assume that the input        le description.txt is as follows.

1

2

0001110011

0001000010

0001000010

1110111011

1001010010

1001100011

0001000010

0000000010

1111111101

1001010010

The le party.txt should be empty. No valid party can be formed from this group of 10 people.

- Racing Gems

You are playing a racing game. Your character starts at the x axis line (y = 0) and proceeds up the racetrack, which has a boundary at the line x = 0 and x = w. The nish is at y = h, and the game ends when you reach that line. You proceed at a xed vertical velocity v, but you can control your horizontal velocity to be any value between v=r and v=r, and change it at any time.

There are a set of gems at speci c points on the race track. Your job is to maximize the total value of the gems that you collect. Each gems has a value associated with it.

What is the maximum value of the gems that your player can collect? You may start at any horizontal position you want (but your vertical position must be 0 at the start).

Input will be in the le gems.txt. The rst line will contain four integers, separated by commas: n (the number of gems), r (the ratio of vertical velocity to maximum horizontal speed), w (the width of the track), and h (the height of the nish line). Following this will be n lines, each containing an x and y coordinate, the coordinates of the gem, and a value v for the gem. All gems will lie within the race track.

Your program will list o the gems that your racer will pick up in chrono-logical order, one per line, in the le race.txt.

For example, we might have a racecourse of length 10, a width of 10, and you had the same potential horizontal velocity as vertical. If there are 5 equally-valued gems on the racetrack, the input le gems.txt might look as follows.

5,1.,10.,10.

8.,8.,1

5.,1.,1

4.,6.,1

4.,7.,1

7.,9.,1

To maximize our pro t, we would only choose three of them in race.txt. The output le looks as follows.

5.0,1.0,1

4.0,7.0,1

- Mixtures

How to make gold from lead has ba ed alchemists for centuries. Scientists recently announced a sensational breakthrough. By mixing N di erent chemi-cals in exactly the correct ratio, one can create a mixture that transforms lead into gold. However, these N chemicals are not found in nature individually but rather only in speci c ratios in liquid form. So making the correct mixture is not as trivial as it may at rst seem.

Consider the following example where N = 3 with chemicals A; B; C. As-sume that two mixtures are available in liquid form in the ratios of 1:2:3 and 3:7:1, respectively. By mixing those two solutions together in the ratio 1:2, it is possible to obtain a solution of A; B; C with ratio 7:16:5, but there is no way to combine these two mixtures into a new one with ratio 3:4:5. However, if we added a solution solution of A; B; C with ratio 2:1:2:, then a 3:4:5 mixture is possible with eight parts of 1:2:3, one part 3:7:1, and 5 parts of 2:1:2.

So clearly, determining which mixing ratios can be obtained from a given set of solution is not trivial. It is your goal in this assignment to do so.

Your input le will be called solutions.txt. The top line will be a line with a desired solution ratio in the form a1 : a2 : a3 : : : : : aN. The next M lines will be the base solution ratios.

Your output le (answer.txt) will consists of M lines, each containing a single integer. These will indicate the parts necessary to get the desired solution. If no solution is possible, then return the value 1 on each line.

So, for example above, the input        le solutions.txt would look as follows:

3:4:5

1:2:3

3:7:1

2:1:2

and the output        le answer.txt would look as follows:

8

1

5
